  "text": "It has been previously reported that extracellular ATP may provide per se a potent antitumor effect [CITATION_1] . To further investigate this, two groups of mice were treated with Phosphate-Buffered Saline (PBS) or non-radioactive ATP using a dosage which is several orders of magnitude higher than that used in the 32 P-ATP treatment. In this setting, we did not find any appreciable difference in tumor growth rate between ATP treated and control tumors ( Figure 1E-G) . This demonstrates that, at least in our model, the antitumor effect of the 32 P-ATP treatment is mainly due to the radioactivity and not because of the intrinsic properties of ATP per se.",
